Creating the main dataset

df_uk<-
    uk_hpi %>%
    select("RegionName", "SalesVolume", "Date", "FlatPrice") %>%
    filter(RegionName == "United Kingdom")%>%
    arrange(Date) %>%
    mutate(SalesVolumelag1 = lag(SalesVolume, 1))%>%
    mutate(FlatPricelag1 = lag(FlatPrice))%>%
    drop_na(SalesVolumelag1)%>%
    drop_na(FlatPricelag1)%>%
    arrange(desc(Date))

The dataset is sorted in ascending order first just in case to prevent spillovers in the lag. Then it is sorted by date in descending order (for readability).

I retroactively added the variable FlatPrice to the df_uk dataset and lagged it, in order to build a second model.

In order to be able to make predictions, I have lagged variables, but it is important to note that this makes the assumption that future data relies on the relationship between current and previous data. It assumes that the predictor helps for forecasting future data, but if the future data doesnât follow that same relationship, the predictions risk being inaccurate.

Model 1: sales volume

lin_model <-
    linear_reg() %>%
    set_engine("lm") %>%
    fit(SalesVolume ~ SalesVolumelag1, data = df_uk_train)
lin_model %>% tidy()

The lagged sales volume data is used as a predictor for sales volume in a linear model, hence the variable name lin_model. This model gives an intercept of 33,725.63 and a slope of 0.5780873, indicating a moderate slope.

The first modelâs fit

aug_lin_model <- lin_model %>% augment(df_uk_train)

This fits the a model to the training dataset and adds columns containing the predicted values and residuals for each row.

plot_df_uk_train <- lin_model %>% augment(df_uk_train)
g_train <- ggplot(plot_df_uk_train, aes(x = .pred, y = .resid)) +
    geom_point(alpha=0.2, size=3, color="red", stroke=1) +
    geom_hline(yintercept = 0, linetype = "dashed") +
    labs(x = "Fitted values", y = "Residuals", title="Residuals vs Fitted") + 
    theme_bw() +

          axis.text.x = element_text(size = rel(1.2)),
          axis.title.y = element_text(size = rel(1.2)),
          axis.text.y = element_text(size = rel(1.2)),
          plot.title = element_text(size = rel(1.5), face = "bold"))

Warning: Removed 9 rows containing missing values (`geom_point()`).

Plotting the relationship between the fitted values and residuals shows no clear pattern to the scatter of points: this is a good sign for the modelâs fit.

mae_train <- 
    lin_model%>% 
    augment(df_uk_train) %>%
    mae(truth = SalesVolume, estimate = .pred)
mae_train
# A tibble: 1 Ã 3
  .metric .estimator .estimate
  <chr>   <chr>          <dbl>
1 mae     standard      13771.

Next, this calculates the mean absolute error for the training set. The model is on average off from the training data by 13771.43 units. This is a very large number but the sales volume data for the entire United Kingdom is much larger than for the individual regions: it is probably the sum of the sales volume data of each region. The residuals for very large predicted numbers are very large, in accordance.

The interquartile range of the training dataset did indeed show a large interquartile range (27461 for SalesVolume, 29598 for SalesVolumelag1), indicating a large range of values.

Using base R functions, Iâll obtain diagnostic plots.

base_r_model <- lm(SalesVolume ~ SalesVolumelag1, data = df_uk_train)
par(mfrow = c(2, 2))
plot(base_r_model)

These shows the relationship is not totally linear, but there is a more or less straight line in the Q-Q plot, showing that the residuals are approximately normally distributed.

Testing the first model

Iâll now use the model to predict the sales volume, based on the lagged sales volume, on the testing dataset. Thereâs no need to train a new model, because df_uk_test has the same variables as the ones the model was trained on, in df_uk_train.

First, I augment the testing set to obtain the modelâs prediction for it, and then I calculate the MAE.

lin_model %>% 
    augment(df_uk_test) %>%
    mae(truth = SalesVolume, estimate = .pred)
# A tibble: 1 Ã 3
  .metric .estimator .estimate
  <chr>   <chr>          <dbl>
1 mae     standard      22682.

The error is quite a bit higher than for the training dataset. This may be because the model is not taking enough predicting factors into account, and is therefore not capturing the changes that occur between the training and testing datasets.

plot_df_uk_test <- lin_model %>% augment(df_uk_test)

Running a scatter plot of the residuals shows that this isnât such a great fit since there does seem to be a pattern to the scatter.

base_r_test_model <- lm(SalesVolume ~ SalesVolumelag1, data = df_uk_test)
par(mfrow = c(2, 2))
plot(base_r_test_model)

The Scale-Location and Residuals vs Leverage lines are far from straight, indicating further that this model isnât such a good fit. I can try using more predictors to see if the model becomes more suited.

Model 2: flat price

It is reasonable to assuem that flat price changes are likely to affect sales, so letâs add FlatPriceslag1 to the model and call it lin_model_2. However, as I have had to delete rows containing missing values for flat prices, it is possible that this addition restricts the amount of data that is avaible to train the model.

lin_model_2 <-
    linear_reg() %>%
    set_engine("lm") %>%
    fit(SalesVolume ~ SalesVolumelag1 + FlatPricelag1, data = df_uk_train)
summary(lin_model_2$fit)

Testing model 2

The error is higher here than for the training dataset. Maybe past flat price changes donât explain much variance in sales volume either, or maybe this model is overfitting, because it is too aligned to the training dataset.

However, this second model is a little bit lower than for the previous modelâs prediction (22682.29-21379.47=1302.82). Therefore, the second model is to be preferred slightly better as it gives very slightly more accurate predictions.

I used ChatGPT in order to understand several ways to visually determine a linear modelâs fit (namely, through the Q-Q plot and through the absence of patterns in the plot of residuals).

I also used ChatGPT to verify the regular notation of the scientific lin_model tidy estimates.
